ADMIN_-_notes_about_person:
Kingston had told me that he didn’t want to come back to boxing because he said the other kids were bullying him and saying he was weird, he told me he experiences similar things at school and he has told his parents that he doesn’t want to return. I spoke to him and told him that I will speak to the class and explain our gyms policy on bullying. I then assured him that if this was to happen again the kids would be removed from the gym. 
 

 I was taking the boxing class and as I noticed Kingston drifting off in the back not paying attention to the lesson, I then asked him privately if everything was ok as this behaviour was not normal from him. He told me he was sad that he couldn’t do the sparring classes, I explained that the people in that class have been at the gym for a long time and they didn’t just get put into it for the fun of it. I told him to keep training and he could get in there in no time.
 

 I was finishing the 4:45 class and Kingston came and talked to me about how he got into a fight at school because he was being bullied, I asked if he was ok and he said he just had a headache. He said the boys would pick on him every day after school when he was walking to the bus and he couldn’t take it anymore. I told him he needs to tell his teachers, or the bullying would never stop. I asked him why and how he could’ve walked away from these altercations and he told me about his anger problems. I spoke to him about some breathing techniques that help me in boxing to slow down my heart rate and make me focus.
 

 Thursday after training I asked Kingston if he had any siblings, and he told me he had a lot of younger siblings and that he would have to baby sit a lot when he was at home especially because of his parents being at work. He told me his little siblings would fear what would happen in the house, and I recommended bringing his younger siblings to the boxing gym, he said this would be a good idea and help them become more confident in scary situations.
 

 Kingston told me after training about how his father would bully him and send him to the gym to become stronger because he was too weak. He explained how his father would always put him down no matter what he did, and that he just wants to make his dad proud, I told him if he needed me to speak to his father and he insisted I shouldn’t so I told him that he had the perfect opportunity to make his dad proud by training hard and becoming stronger.
 

 Kingston had brought a vape to training and the other kids all asked him to use it and he ended up losing it, he brought this issue up when I asked him what was wrong, I brought the class in and said they wouldn’t be training for the week unless someone owned up to stealing his vape, until someone owned up I explained that we don’t tolerate theft in the gym as we are all a family and I told them that they shouldn’t even be vaping as lung cancer is the leading cause of death in new Zealand. I told the class that vapes would be banned at training from now on.

Mose had come to me about his issue with finding it difficult to learn new things and that he was afraid of messing up. I confided with him that I was the same and that I used to be afraid to fail until I started fighting, just trying is the most important step in losing your fears he told me that he has been like this since he was little. He told me that his older siblings laugh at him for failing at school and say that he won’t get far in life. I told him to continue with his training and to try just as hard in his homework because its important to balance everything in your life.
 

 During our sprint training near the end of class Mose had run off as he was upset about being last in the 100m sprints, I saw him crying at the end of the street, he told me that he was tired of being last even though he tries his hardest, I told him that there’s always room for improvement even when you think there isn’t that’s what separates the normal people and the champions, I told him he will be tested in this sport and he can either run from it or face it with grit and determination. 
 

 Mose told me during training that his mum was moving to Australia and he would be living with his dad here, his dad wanted him to go because he was hanging around the wrong crowd and going down the wrong path. I asked him why he was hanging around with these types of people as he was doing so well at training and he was improving. He told me he wants to fit in with the crowd and that he likes it when he is praised even when he does something wrong because it makes him feel like he’s succeeding. I told him where he would end up if he continues hanging around with the wrong people and that his school counsellor would be a good person to talk to about how they feel as I can only help them so much.
 

 Before class had started Mose told me that his friends were arrested during a ram raid and I asked if he was involved he told me he didn’t go with them because he realised what his actions could cause and that he won’t hang out with them anymore, I told him the boxing gym is the best place to be praised as you are praised for your hard work and discipline instead of something negative, and that if he keeps up his efforts he will make himself proud which is the most important thing.
 

 Mose told me that there was a fight at school while we were sitting before class started, he told me how the year 13’s started fighting behind the gym and that he just sat and watched instead of calling someone to come break it up. He said he was scared of being a “snitch” and that he was scared of being attacked by them I told him that the best thing you can do in these situations is get help because they could escalate and someone could get hurt, even if it means “snitching”.

I sat with Tamiti for 10 minutes and we talked about his confidence. i explained to Tamiti that failure is a part of success, that every person that was in the room has failed countless times and continues to fail. but that's what helps them to learn and without failing we are not learning. Tamiti seemed to resonate with this and gave Coach Levi a hug and said thank you.

 After we had finished training juneyt came to talk to me about his weight being an issue with training, he asked if he was too big to be a boxer and that he had struggle breathing during training. I told him these are normal thoughts to experience, he told me that he is bullied at school about his weight and that no one listens to him when he tries to talk to them. I told him I could speak to his parents or teachers about this issue and that boxing is the best thing for him both physically and mentally.
 

 Juneyt told me about how he would be getting into fights at intermediate and how he would get bullied so his only way to defend himself was by hitting others. He talked to me about how none of his teachers understood him and they would ignore him without understanding where he was coming from. I talked to him and he said he wanted to change and become less violent, I talked to him about starting boxing and letting his anger out in the gym instead of on other people. 
 

 After boxing Juneyt told me that he was really enjoying boxing and that he was getting into less fights at school I asked him why this was happening, he told me his weight loss was a big part of this as he wasn’t being picked on anymore and that he was feeling fitter at training. I told him I was glad to hear this and that he would always have a place at the gym and to keep up his training.
 

 Juneyt told me before class started that his parents used to argue all the time before they divorced and his mum always blames the divorce on him he told me that he always cries in his room because his mum always belittles him and blames everything on him. I told him that I would speak to her about this, I recommended therapy to his mother for both Juneyt and her as they both had issues that they needed to get off their chest.
 

 I heard the kids belittling Juneyt and calling him names when he walked in so I asked everyone to apologise to him, I talked to everyone about how they would feel if they were being called these things I told the class that this would be the last time that this would happen if it didn’t they would be removed from the gym immediately.

I overheard Andreas and his brother talking about fighting other kids at school and I asked them why they wanted to fight outside of the gym and they both said that they get really angry and cant control their temper, I told them that they could compete for the gym in amateur boxing tournaments instead of fighting in the street if that’ll help them with their anger problems. The training at the gym is very tiring and it’ll leave them feeling too exhausted to fight other people. 
 

 I was talking to Andreas about his anger issues and he said that whenever he feels slightly agitated, he breaks, and he lashes out at everything and anyone. I asked him how long he’s felt like this and he said since he started intermediate, he said he’s been kicked out of schools for fighting and that he wants to change but his teachers don’t understand that he can’t control it. I told him that he’s just recently started boxing and that he will learn to control his anger more during boxing training as you learn to control your breathing which slows down your heart rate and makes you calm down.
 

 Andreas told me that he wanted to come to the gym more often because he didn’t want to be at home to see his parents fighting and arguing. I told him that he is always welcome to come when he needs to talk to someone or to let his anger out on the bag or on the pads. He told me they’ve been arguing about not having enough money and telling the young kids they need to work. I asked Andreas wanted and he said he just didn’t want to be at home, so I told him to apply to some part time jobs and I would be a reference to help him get a job.
 

 Andreas and one of the other kids were arguing during class and they started swearing and yelling at each other I separated them both and spoke to them both individually about why they were arguing and they said they didn’t like each other, I told them both that we didn’t have to like each other to enjoy training, and that the gym is where we can let go of our emotions and let go of our negative feelings. 
 

 During training Andreas was yelling across the road at some kids from another school and I told him to come inside and I asked why he was yelling he said that the kids wanted to fight him because he was dating one of the boys sisters, I told him that we should talk to the boys and try come to a conclusion so I called the boys into the boxing gym and they talked about how Andreas loves her and that he always takes care of her. The boys just didn’t want to see her get hurt.

 Spoke to Mum she has said that she really enjoys having a female coach who supports her. Dayna may not show it but she is always talking about her coach on her way home.

 Dayna and I have talked about making new friends with the girls in the Gym. She has recently made a new friend in class and is walking in with a smile. We spoke after class about how her behavior is really starting to change and turn around 
 

 Recently spoke with Dayna's mum as she is coming into class and doesn't seem happy, Mum has said she has been the same at home, Really moody, Mum is worried that her group of friends from school has changed and will have a chat with her this week.

Serenity lives with her Aunty. Mum was recently in Jail. She has shown a lot attitude in classes. I spoke with her about having good values. i have asked her about why she chose boxing, She said to me that she hates the fitness but wants to learn how to fight better 
 

 Spoke with Serenity today as she was really disengaged from class, during our circle of highlights she stated that her highlight was beating another girl up at school. We spoke about her attitude in the values of our gym, we stood her down for a week as she has broken our fighting outside of the gym rule. 
 

 Aunty came in today and we spoke about serenity, she was saying that she is improving here but doesn't want to show it. she can see her confidence growing, but is still struggling with anger.
 

 Serenity and myself sat down after class and talked about why she gets angry and gives up in class, she has disclosed that she feels like her life is meaningless and that nobody was ever there for her. I offered my support to help her manage these emotions.
 

 Serenity has spoken to me about helping the new kids we get in class, she feels confident enough to teach them the basic skills of boxing, she has become more engaged in class so I have made a plan for her to help run classes.

I sat with Tamiti for 10 minutes and we talked about his confidence. i explained to Tamiti that failure is a part of success, that every person that was in the room has failed countless times and continues to fail. but that's what helps them to learn and without failing we are not learning. Tamiti seemed to resonate with this and gave Coach Levi a hug and said thank you.
